Cape Town - Stellenbosch Football Club (SFC) is mourning the loss of young promising defender, Oshwin Andries, who was killed in a stabbing on Saturday.  Police spokesperson Captain Nowonga Sukwana said the 19-year-old died in hospital.  “Oshwin Andries passed away in hospital on February 4 at 9.40pm after his family took him to hospital. He was treated for a stab wound and discharged. His family then took him to Paarl hospital. The circumstances around his stabbing are still under investigation,” she said.  Andries was a gifted young footballer who graduated from the SFC Academy to make his professional debut at the age of 18, the club said. He later became the Club’s youngest-ever goalscorer in the DStv Premiership, and also captained South Africa at the recent U-20 Afcon Cosafa qualifiers. The club said his presence, both on the pitch and off, will be sorely missed. “It is with deep sadness that Stellenbosch FC has learnt of the untimely passing of promising young defender, Oshwin Andries. The club is not in a position to provide further information at this stage and asks that his family’s privacy be respected in this difficult time of bereavement. The thoughts and prayers of everyone at Stellenbosch FC are with his family, friends and loved ones.”  The Premier Soccer League said it was shocked and saddened by the news of his passing. “The PSL is shocked and saddened by the untimely passing of young Stellenbosch FC defender, Oshwin Andries.  “The league sends heartfelt condolences to the Andries family, Stellenbosch FC, and the football fraternity at large. May his soul repose peacefully.” Condolences and tributes have been pouring in for Andries on social media.  Cape Times